attributes.title: Association between Helicobacter pylori infection and celiac disease: A systematic review and meta‐analysis of observational studies

q1.value: Association between Helicobacter pylori infection and celiac disease: A systematic review and meta‐analysis of observational studies

q3.value: Previous studies have reported on the relationship between Helicobacter pylori infection and celiac disease risk, while the results remain controversial and inconsistent. Hence, we conducted a meta-analysis to comprehensively evaluate this relationship.

q4.value: Helicobacter pylori may increase or decrease the risk of celiac disease.

q5.value: Meta-Analysis - A systematic review of published studies.

value: No blinding is involved in this study.

question.value: Observational studies (case-control, cross-sectional, and cohort studies) published as original articles investigating the association between Helicobacter pylori infection and celiac disease will be included.

q10.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value: We searched the PubMed, EMBASE, and Web of Science databases for relevant studies  from inception to February, 2020, without language restrictions. Observational studies (cross-sectional, case-control, and cohort studies) published as original articles investigating the association between Helicobacter pylori infection and celiac disease will be included. Exclusion criteria were as follows: (i) Irrelevant literatures, duplicate studies;(ii)letters, comments, case-report, laboratory studies, reviews and meta-analyses; (iii)Data unavailable studies.

q13.value: At least 5 studies will be included in our meta-analysis

question.value: The prevalence of celiac disease infected by Helicobacter pylori.

We used the Review Manager 5.3 software to perform meta-analyses. The odds ratio (OR) and  95% confidence intervals (CI) was used as a measure of association between Helicobacter pylori and the celiac disease. Cochran's Q test and I² statistic were used to evaluate the statistical heterogeneity between the studies. The significance for the Q test was defined as P 0.10. I2 values of 0-25%, 26-50%, 51-75% and above 75% indicated low, moderate, high and very high heterogeneity, respectively. We used a random-effect model (REM) to analyze the data for the outcome. Subgroup analyses and sensitivity analyses were applied to find out the source of heterogeneity. If possible, we will conduct further meta-regression analysis to explore the source of heterogeneity. If the number of included studies was more than five in a meta-analysis, we used funnel plots to evaluate the publication bias. Besides, Egger’s test were further conducted to quantitatively detect publication bias risk by STATA/SE 12.0.

attributes.title: Open Research Practice Questionnaire 2020; University of Surrey

data.value: No, no data have been collected for this study yet.

name.value: Open Research Practice Questionnaire 2020; University of Surrey

other.value: A major part of the output of this questionnaire is to provide descriptive statistics, including figures, showing how the sample performs on each item and scale. These will provide the first benchmarks of Open Research Practice use, perceptions and training needs at the University of Surrey.

sample.value: The goal of this study is to recruit a representative sample of research active staff at the University of Surrey. Current response rates for this kind of questionnaire are approximately 20%. Hence, we will aim for a minimum 20% response rate.

analyses.value:
For each of 14 questions in the questionnaire, descriptive statistics will be reported with respect to the raw count and the percentage of respondents for each response type. For Research Questions 1 to 3 this will be presented as follows: 
1.	All data
2.	All data, split by career level. The levels given are: Professor, Reader, Senior lecturer, Lecturer, Professional Services, Post-doctoral researcher ≤5 years post-PhD, Post-doctoral researcher >5 years post-PhD, Postgraduate researcher (PhD student), Graduate research assistant, other. If responses are low, these categories will be collapsed as follows: Professor+Reader, Senior lecturer+Lecturer, Post-doctoral researcher ≤5 years post-PhD+>5 years post-PhD, Postgraduate researcher (PhD student)+Graduate research assistant, Professional Services+other.
3.	All data split by Faculty (Faculty of Health and Medical Sciences, Faculty of Engineering and Physical Sciences, Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences. Note that the Department of Higher Education and Technology Enhanced Learning are support departments. Responses from these departments will be included with the Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences).
Questions 4, 5 and 6 will be analysed using Chi-Squared, provided the data meet the assumptions for using Chi-Squared (expected cell frequencies are ≥5). Where there is insufficient data, descriptive statistics only will be reported. 
4.	Chi-squared (one per Open Research Practice): Using and/or accessing (two levels: ticked vs. not ticked) by level of importance of each Open Research Practice (three levels: Very important+important, neutral, Very unimportant+unimportant).
5.	Chi-squared: Using and/or accessing (three levels: ticked ‘using and/or accessing’ for 0 to 2, 3 to 5, 6 to 8 Open Research Practices) by use of Open Research Team (library) services (three levels: ticked ‘I don’t use / didn’t know about’, ticked ‘use’ for 1 to 6 services, ticked ‘use’ for 6 to 12 services).
6.	Chi-squared: Using and/or accessing (three levels: ticked ‘using and/or accessing’ for 0 to 2, 3 to 5, 6 to 8 Open Research Practices) by Surrey Reproducibility Society (two levels: Yes / No).

outliers.value:
1. Completion Rules: We have designed this questionnaire so that participants cannot progress without answering (where appropriate) all items. For participants who fail to complete the questionnaire, i.e., stop mid-way through, their responses will only be included for scales (DV’s) where they have provided an answer. 
2. Career level and Faculty Response Rates: If there are fewer than 10 responses from a given Career level or Faculty university, these participants will be excluded from all analyses for which the data is split by Career level or Faculty. 
3. Minimum time cap: The shortest amount of time that can be taken to meaningfully complete this questionnaire will be categorised as a completion time that is -3.29 standard deviations from the mean completion time. Anyone with a full set of responses and a completion time that is shorter than this time, will be excluded from all analyses. 
4. Open Answer Questions: For items where participants have to write an answer, instead of selecting from a set of tick boxes, participants will be excluded from any analysis based on this item, if their response is inappropriate or incomprehensible.

dependent.value:
Interest in Open Research Practice: 5-point likert scale from ‘Yes, very’ to ‘Not at all’ and ‘Other’ (Q1).

Awareness and use of Open Research Practices: Eight item scale (8 Open Research Practices; Open access, Open data/sharing data, Open software/code, Study preregistration, Preprint archiving, Open monographs, Open licences, ORCID identifier) with three responses available: Aware of, Practicing myself, Accessing/Using (Q2).

Perceptions of the importance of adopting Open Research Practices (8 Open Research Practices as above). 5-point likert scale from ‘Very unimportant’ to ‘Very important’ (Q3, Q4).

Perceptions of barriers and incentives to adopting Open Research Practices / Open data: Tick all that apply (Q5, Q9, Q10); Which is the greatest barrier? (Q6); Open text box (these will be categorised into themes to extract frequencies by theme) (Q7, Q8). 

Training needs (All questions are ‘Tick all that apply’): Where do you receive training about open research practices (Q11); Which services offered by the Open Research Team at the library do you make use of (Q12); Which of the following open research methods would you like to receive more information about? (Q14)

Membership of Surrey Reproducibility Society: Yes / No (Q13).

conditions.value: There is no allocation to conditions in this study

hypothesis.value:
The primary aim of this research is to investigate: awareness and use of Open Research Practices; perceptions of the importance of and the barriers and incentives to adopting Open Research Practices; as well as to determine training needs at the University of Surrey. 
For each of 14 questions regarding Open Research Practices, we will ask:
1.	What is the frequency of each response choice?
2.	Does the frequency of each response choice differ by career level?
3.	Does the frequency of each response choice differ by Faculty?
4.	Are frequencies of perceptions of the importance of each Open Research Practice associated with frequencies of experience with using and/or accessing that Open Research Practice?
5.	Are frequencies of use of Open Research Team (library) services associated with frequencies of experience with using and/or accessing that Open Research Practice?
6.	Is membership of the Surrey Reproducibility Society (Yes / No) associated with frequencies of experience with using and/or accessing that Open Research Practice?

attributes.title: Acupuncture for postoperative care of anterior cruciate ligament reconstruction : a systematic review and meta-analysis

q1.value: Acupuncture for postoperative care of anterior cruciate ligament reconstruction : a systematic review and meta-analysis

q3.value:
Main review question : "Is acupuncture effective for postoperative care of anterior cruciate ligament reconstruction?"

The anterior cruciate ligament(ACL) is an important sstablilizing ligament of the knee that is frequently injured by athletes and trauma victims. There are between 100,000 and 200,000 ACL ruptures per year in the United States alone. Appropriate treatment for an anterior cruciate ligament (ACL) injury depends upon the extent of injury, patient characteristics and activities, and available resources. Mostly, younger patients with high-level activity opt for surgical reconstruction. When deciding to treat a complete ACL rupture nonoperatively, there are risks of osteorarthritis and subsequent knee injury. ACL reconstruction is generally performed with arthroscopy using a graft to replace the ruptured ACL using patellar tendon, hamstring tendon(semitendinosus and gracilis), or quadriceps tendon. After reconstruction, the main target of rehabilitation program is to regain normal range of motion, especially in knee extension. Usually closed kinetic chain exercises to strengthen the hamstring and quadriceps muscle are effective for initial rehabilitation and then continuously combined with open chain exercises. Exercise to enhance balance, proprioception, and core strength should be incorporated.

q4.value: If acupuncture combined with conventional rehabilitation program effective for postoperative care after anterior cruciate ligament reconstruction, then pain, range of motion, functional scale of knee joint and muscle strength will be much improved than that of conventional rehabilitation course group.

q5.value: Meta-Analysis - A systematic review of published studies.

value: Personnel who analyze the data collected from the study are not aware of the treatment applied to any given group.

question.value: Systematic review and meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials.

q10.value: Registration prior to creation of data

q13.value: There are no size requirements for this study. Several RCTs extracted by search strategies will be included.

question.value:
Main outcome
1. 100mm Visual analogue scale (VAS) will be the primary outcome. 10cm VAS will be transformed into 100mm VAS. Because the most chief complaint of the patients are pain, it can show the effectiveness of acupuncture appropriately.

Additional outcome
1. Range of motion of knee joint
2. Lysholm knee scoring scale 
3. Circumference of knee joint, indicator of joint swelling after surgery
4. Manual muscle testing grade

Meta-analysis will be conducted with the imported data by the Comprehensive Meta Analysis V.2. individual participant data will be used and a quantitative synthesis is planned. After calculating statistical heterogeneity with the Cochran Q statistic and I² statistic, the model of analysis will be decided. When I²>50%, random-effect model will be used, otherwise fixed effect model. 5 to 7 researchers will be involved in this study and if there is discrepancy among those, the main author (Hokyung Chang) will hold a discussion for it and make a final decision.

If the heterogeneity is large, subgroup analysis will be conducted as follows:
1. type of acupuncture
2. other combined traditional chinese medicine therapy
3. duration of treatment
4. period from the onset of anterior cruciate ligament injury to reconstruction surgery
5. period from the anterior cruciate ligament reconstruction to intervention applied

q23.value: We will try to contact the original investigators by email to request missing data. If the missing data were not obtained, we will analyse only the available data.
